******
[2]
Date: Sat 26 Sep 2009
Source: Minister of Agriculture
Nature and Food Quality letter to Parliament, ref VDC 09.1803/CPM
[trans. Mod.AS, abridged & edited]
<http://www.minlnv.nl/portal/page?_pageid=116,1640321&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&p_file_id=43042>

Q fever
-------
In addition to the letter of 28 Aug 2009 (2008-2009 Parliamentary
paper: 28 286), I provide you, also on behalf of Minister [of Health]
Klink, the following information on the state of matters relating to
the new approach addressing Q fever. The new approach is aimed at
maintaining the freedom from Q fever of those dairy goats and sheep
farms throughout the Netherlands not yet infected, and the
rehabilitation of the Q fever-infected farms.

We assume that by addressing the main sources of infection in sheep
and goats, the Q-fever epidemic in humans is to be controlled.

Bulk tank milk monitoring
------------------------
Starting 1 Oct 2009, holders of more than 50 dairy goats or sheep
will be obliged to participate in the Q-fever monitoring. For this
purpose, each farm will be sampled once in 2 months for Q-fever
testing. Suspected/positive samples will be forwarded for
confirmatory testing to the Central Veterinary Institute (CVI). If
confirmed, those farms will be declared infected.

Measures applied in infected farms
----------------------------------
Hygienic measures:

Pending the outcome of the ongoing investigation into improved manure
handling procedures, the current, published measures are to be
maintained. This means that throughout the lambing season and up to
30 days after its termination, no manure is permitted to be mucked
out. The spread of manure in the fields will be allowed only after
additional 90 days of storage under cover.

- Exit of animals:
Animals are not allowed exit to other farms for milk production or breeding.
The transportation of animals to slaughterhouses is permitted.
Animals under the age of 4 weeks are allowed transportation to fattening units.

- Introduction of animals:
Infected farms are allowed to introduce only vaccinated animals from
Q fever-free farms.

- Visits ban:
No visitors are allowed on infected premises.

- Vaccination:
Infected farms must vaccinate all their animals.

Measures applied in free holdings:
------------------------------------
- There are no restrictions upon the handling/use of manure, or upon
exit of animals from free holdings.

- Introduction of animals is allowed only from Q fever-free holdings.

- Vaccination: Free holdings should be vaccinated.

Policy regarding the fate of infected farms:
-------------------------------------------
Infected Dairy goats and sheep farms may regain their free status
after a year of negative bi-monthly bulk tank milk test results. This
period is relatively long due to uncertainties concerning the pattern
of excretion of the Q-fever pathogen and the role thereupon of the
lambing season.

Pilot studies, aiming at the identification of additional measures to
obtain early eradication of the disease on infected farms, have been
undertaken by the CVI and the Animal Health Service (GD).

Manure treatment:
----------------
As stated in the letter of 28 Aug 2009, industrial composting of
manure was to be experimentally investigated as an alternative to its
incineration. Meanwhile, a request to carry out such investigation
has been received from the province Zuid-Holland. This research is
being addressed by the CVI and the Animal Science Group. The results
of this investigation is expected before the next lambing season.

Vaccination Campaign 2010:
-------------------------
During 2010, vaccination will be compulsory throughout the
Netherlands, including all holdings of more than 50 sheep or dairy
goats, all animals on children's farms, care farms and zoos.
Vaccination will be also compulsory in wandering sheep flocks, in
nature reserves and on farms holding lamb petting days. In other
sheep and goat holdings, vaccination will be voluntary.

The number of available vaccine doses is sufficient for the
vaccination of all the above described holdings. For the vaccination
campaign of 2010, 1.5 million doses of vaccine are available, of
which 100 000 doses are to be delivered in November 2009. The rest of
the vaccine doses will become available during 2010. The precise
delivery schedule is still being negotiated with the vaccine
manufacturer. We strive, of course, for the earliest possible
delivery.

[signed]
Gerda Verburg
Minister of Agriculture, Nature and Food Safety

